<p><b>Simon Michael Schama</b>, <a href="/wiki/Order_of_the_British_Empire" title="Order of the British Empire">CBE</a> (born 13 February 1945) is a British professor of history and <a href="/wiki/Art_history" title="Art history">art history</a> at <a href="/wiki/Columbia_University" title="Columbia University">Columbia University</a>. His many works on <a href="/wiki/History" title="History">history</a> and <a href="/wiki/Art" title="Art">art</a> include <i>Landscape and Memory</i>, <i>Dead Certainties</i>, <i>Rembrandt's Eyes</i>, and his history of the <a href="/wiki/French_Revolution" title="French Revolution">French Revolution</a>, <i><a href="/wiki/Citizens_(book)" title="Citizens (book)">Citizens</a></i>. He is best known for writing and hosting the 15-part <a href="/wiki/BBC" title="BBC">BBC</a> documentary series <i><a href="/wiki/Simon_Schama%27s_A_History_of_Britain" title="Simon Schama's A History of Britain" class="mw-redirect">A History of Britain</a></i>. He was an art and cultural critic for <i><a href="/wiki/The_New_Yorker" title="The New Yorker">The New Yorker</a></i>.</p>
